 a utopian wish to reach women and correspond with them across similarities and differences. To make the artwork’s aspirations more concrete, it places the artists in correspondence with three writers – Angela Davis, Valerie Solanas, and Laura Mulvey – who also addressed the limited range of images through which women are allowed to become visible.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt and literature. 0aFeminism and art. 0aFeminist art criticism. 0aOther (Philosophy) in art. 0aOther (Philosophy) in literature. 0aWomen in art. 0aWomen in literature. 7aART / History / Contemporary (1945-).2bisacsh  aAddress.  aAdrian Piper.  aAggression.  aBlack Feminism.  aCodex Artaud.  aFeminist Art.  aFeminist Imaginary.  aFeminist Publics.  aFeminist Visual Studies.  aFeminist Writing.  aMary Kelly.  aMaternal Femininity.  aNancy Spero.  aPost-Partum Document.  aRacism.  aTextual Correspondences.  aThe Sign Woman.  ablack female body.  afantasies.  afears.  aimages of writing.  avisual compositions.  awomen artists.1 aLamm, Kimberly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2018 eBook-Packagez978311128277040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152612598940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526125989423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526125989/original  a978-3-11-128277-0  Manchester University Press 2018 eBook-Packageb2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles